  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">ACCESS TO JUSTICE FOR THE VULNERABLE</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Through its 34 member organisations, LAF will strengthen the professional capacity of legal aid providers in rural areas to effectively provide quality and accessible legal aid services; undertake research, lobby and advocacy to ensure that legal aid policy and implementation framework are conducive for enhanced legal aid provision; make the Legal Aid Forum an effective and sustainable membership-based network of legal aid providers committed to advancing access to justice. They will operate throughout the Republic of Rwanda with the secretariat being based in Kigali.

The principal target groups are organisations engaged in the provision of legal aidservices to the indigent and vulnerable groups in Rwanda through the structure of the Legal Aid Forum,encompassing national and international NGOs, international organisations, professional bodies (the Rwandan Bar Association and the Corps of Judicial Defenders),trade unions and university legal clinics.

Target groups also include institutions and organisations involved in the Justice Sector (including the 14 institution members of the Justice Sector, such as the Ministry of Justice, the Ministry of Internal Security, the Judiciary, the National Commission for Human Rights, the Office of the Ombudsman, the National Prison Service, the Rwanda National Police, the National Public Prosecution Authorities, etc.) together with the Parliament, in view of a conducive legal aid regulatory and policy framework.

The indigent and vulnerable groups are the direct beneficiaries, and will be facilitated to attain a broadened understanding of their rights and the legal framework, settlement of disputes and unjust practices in a more timely and efficient fashion, and greater access to legal advice and representation. Vulnerable groups include women, children, youth and elderly persons, historically marginalised groups, widows, persons living with HIV/AIDS, disabled persons, former soldiers, displaced persons and refugees, genocide survivors, prisoners and personsin custody in police stations or other detention centres, etc.).</narrative>
  </description>
  <participating-org role="4" type="90">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Legal Aid Forum</narrative>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The idea to form the Forum emerged in 2004 following the first study on legal aid in Rwanda. The study highlighted the determination of NGOs to provide legal aid services to the poor and marginalised Rwandans. Limited collaboration was, however identified as one factor limiting the effectiveness and efficiency of legal aid service provision. The idea emerged to create a space for organisations to share information, best practices, collaborate around capacity building, research and advocacy. The initiative of the Forum is seen as an essential step by NGOs in Rwanda to contribute towards improved rule of law and ruling justly.
 On 26th October 2006, over 30 NGOs endorsed to work together as a loose (informal) local network to meet the following objectives:
1. To increase collaboration and complementarity between activities and actors in the domain of legal aid and access to justice;
2. To improve the quality andaccessibility of legal aid service provision;
3. To reinforce the capacity of interveners in the area of legal aid;
4. To identify and initiate research and advocacy on legal issues affecting indigent population and vulnerable groups in Rwanda;
5. To contribute towards the development of an effective, sustainable legal aid system in Rwanda;
6. To mobilise resources and technical support to enhance legal aid.
Major changes since its creation include changing from an informal network to a formal local network registered under Rwandan law. LAF has been gathering evidence on how gender issues are being mainstreamed into members# activities and therefore some desegregated data exist within LAF records. LAF has now developed a Gender and HIV/AIDS policy which will help LAF and LAF members in mainstreaming gender and HIV/AIDS concepts in the programmes and activities.</narrative>
